data.sign: Do you not see the Yellow River's waters descending from the sky, racing toward the ocean never to return? Do you not see the mirrors in high halls lamenting white hair, like morning's black silk turning to evening snow? When life's joys beckon, drink your fill! Never let a golden cup face the moon in vain. Heaven gave me talents meant for use—scattered gold returns a thousandfold. Cook lamb, butcher oxen—be merry now! Drink three hundred cups without pause. Master Cen, Scholar Danqiu—let the wine flow! Cups must never stop. I'll sing you a song—listen close! Bells and drums, fine dishes—all worthless. Better stay forever drunk than sober. Ancient sages were lonely souls—only drinkers leave their names behind. Prince Chen once feasted at Pingyue, ten thousand coins for wine, wild revelry. Why should a host complain of scant coins? Just fetch more wine and drink with me! My dappled horse, my furs worth fortunes—call the boy to trade them for fine wine! Together we'll drown sorrows ten thousand years old.

North and south of my cottage, spring waters flow; only flocks of gulls come daily to and fro. The flower-strewn path has yet to be swept for guests; the wicker gate opens for you, its first in days. With market far, no varied dishes grace my board; my humble home offers but aged wine. If you'll drink with the old man next door, I'll call him over through the fence to finish the last drops.

The great river flows eastward, sweeping away countless heroes of bygone days. West of the ancient fortress, they say, lies Red Cliff where Zhou Yu won his fame. Jagged rocks pierce clouds, furious waves crash shores, rolling up snow-white drifts. Rivers and mountains paint a timeless scene—how many heroes passed here once! I dream of Zhou Yu in those years: newly wed to the Qiao sisters, valiant and bold. With feather fan and silk cap, he laughed and talked while enemy ships burned to ashes. My spirit wanders ancient lands—too sentimental, mocked by time, my hair turned grey. Life is but a dream—I raise my cup to the river's moon.

Last night, rain sparse, wind fierce; deep sleep did not dispel the lingering wine. I ask the maid rolling up the curtain: "How are the crabapple flowers?" "Same as before," she says. "Don't you know? Don't you know? It should be green leaves flourishing, red flowers thinning."
